[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] In addition, **Narrative visualization** is a method that uses visual elements such as charts, graphs, maps and the like to convey data or information.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] This approach blends data analysis, storytelling, and visualization to present information through structured narrative flows- *using visuals not just to present statistics, but to tell a story through data*.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Its goal is to help people identify trends, patterns, and relationships in data through a compelling story-driven visual experience.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Emerging technologies like virtual, augmented and mixed reality have the potential to make information visualization more immersive, intuitive, interactive and easily manipulable and thus enhance the user's visual perception and cognition.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Effective data visualization is well-sourced, appropriately contextualized, and presented in a simple, uncluttered manner.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The underlying data is accurate and up-to-date to ensure insights are reliable.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Graphical items are well-chosen and aesthetically appealing, with shapes, colors and other visual elements used deliberately in a meaningful and non-distracting manner.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The visuals are accompanied by supporting texts.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Verbal and graphical components complement each other to ensure clear, quick and memorable understanding.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Effective information visualization is aware of the needs and expertise level of the target audience.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Data scientists, analysts and data mining specialists use data visualization to check data quality, find errors, unusual gaps, missing values, clean data, explore the structures and features of data, and assess outputs of data-driven models.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization can be part of *data storytelling*, where they are paired with a narrative structure, to contextualize the analyzed data and communicate insights gained from analyzing it to convince the audience into making a decision or taking action.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization is interdisciplinary, it incorporates principles found in descriptive statistics, visual communication, graphic design, cognitive science and, interactive computer graphics and human-computer interaction.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Since effective visualization requires design skills, statistical skills and computing skills, it is both an art and a science.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Visual analytics combines statistical data analysis, data and information visualization, and human analytical reasoning through interactive visual interfaces to help users reach conclusions, gain actionable insights and make informed decisions which are otherwise difficult for computers to do.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Research into how people read and misread types of visualizations helps to determine what types and features of visualizations are most understandable and effective.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Unintentionally poor or intentionally misleading and deceptive visualizations can function as powerful tools which disseminate misinformation, manipulate public perception and divert public opinion.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Thus data visualization literacy has become an important component of data and information literacy in the information age akin to the roles played by textual, mathematical and visual literacy in the past.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The field of data and information visualization has emerged "from research in human–computer interaction, computer science, graphics, visual design, psychology, photography and business methods.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] It is increasingly applied as a critical component in scientific research, digital libraries, data mining, financial data analysis, market studies, manufacturing production control, and drug discovery".
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization presumes that "visual representations and interaction techniques take advantage of the human eye's broad bandwidth pathway into the mind to allow users to see, explore, and understand large amounts of information at once.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Data analysis is an indispensable part of all applied research and problem solving in industry.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Among these approaches, information visualization, or visual data analysis, is the most reliant on the cognitive skills of human analysts, and allows the discovery of unstructured actionable insights that are limited only by human imagination and creativity.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The analyst does not have to learn any sophisticated methods to be able to interpret the visualizations of the data.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Information visualization is also a hypothesis generation scheme, which can be, and is typically followed by more analytical or formal analysis, such as statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] To communicate information clearly and efficiently, data visualization uses statistical graphics, plots, information graphics and other tools.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Numerical data may be encoded using dots, lines, or bars, to visually communicate a quantitative message.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Effective visualization helps users analyze and reason about data and evidence.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] It makes complex data more accessible, understandable, and usable, but can also be reductive.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Users may have particular analytical tasks, such as making comparisons or understanding causality, and the design principle of the graphic (i.e., showing comparisons or showing causality) follows the task.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Tables are generally used where users will look up a specific measurement, while charts of various types are used to show patterns or relationships in the data for one or more variables.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization refers to the techniques used to communicate data or information by encoding it as visual objects (e.g., points, lines, or bars) contained in graphics.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The goal is to communicate information clearly and efficiently to users.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] It is one of the steps in data analysis or data science.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] According to Vitaly Friedman (2008) the "main goal of data visualization is to communicate information clearly and effectively through graphical means.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] It doesn't mean that data visualization needs to look boring to be functional or extremely sophisticated to look beautiful.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] To convey ideas effectively, both aesthetic form and functionality need to go hand in hand, providing insights into a rather sparse and complex data set by communicating its key aspects in a more intuitive way.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Yet designers often fail to achieve a balance between form and function, creating gorgeous data visualizations which fail to serve their main purpose — to communicate information".
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Wattenberg suggested that an ideal visualization should not only communicate clearly, but stimulate viewer engagement and attention.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is closely related to information graphics, information visualization, scientific visualization, exploratory data analysis and statistical graphics.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] In the new millennium, data visualization has become an active area of research, teaching and development.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] (2002), it has united scientific and information visualization.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] In the commercial environment data visualization is often referred to as dashboards.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Infographics are another very common form of data visualization.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Edward Tufte has explained that users of information displays are executing particular *analytical tasks* such as making comparisons.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The *design principle* of the information graphic should support the analytical task.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] As William Cleveland and Robert McGill show, different graphical elements accomplish this more or less effectively.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] For example, dot plots and bar charts outperform pie charts.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] In his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, Edward Tufte defines 'graphical displays' and principles for effective graphical display in the following passage: "Excellence in statistical graphics consists of complex ideas communicated with clarity, precision, and efficiency.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] For example, the Minard diagram shows the losses suffered by Napoleon's army in the 1812–1813 period.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Six variables are plotted: the size of the army, its location on a two-dimensional surface (x and y), time, the direction of movement, and temperature.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The line width illustrates a comparison (size of the army at points in time), while the temperature axis suggests a cause of the change in army size.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] This multivariate display on a two-dimensional surface tells a story that can be grasped immediately while identifying the source data to build credibility.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Not applying these principles may result in misleading graphs, distorting the message, or supporting an erroneous conclusion.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] According to Tufte, chartjunk refers to the extraneous interior decoration of the graphic that does not enhance the message or gratuitous three-dimensional or perspective effects.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Needlessly separating the explanatory key from the image itself, requiring the eye to travel back and forth from the image to the key, is a form of "administrative debris." The ratio of "data to ink" should be maximized, erasing non-data ink where feasible.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The Congressional Budget Office summarized several best practices for graphical displays in a June 2014 presentation.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] These included: a) Knowing your audience; b) Designing graphics that can stand alone outside the report's context; and c) Designing graphics that communicate the key messages in the report.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] For greatest efficiency and simplicity of design and user experience, this readability is enhanced through the use of bijective mapping in that design of the image elements - where the mapping of representational element to data variable is unique.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Kosara (2007) also identifies the need for a visualisation to be "recognisable as a visualisation and not appear to be something else".
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] He also states that recognisability and readability may not always be required in all types of visualisation e.g.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] "informative art" (which would still meet all three above criteria but might not look like a visualisation) or "artistic visualisation" (which similarly is still based on non-visual data to create an image, but may not be readable or recognisable).
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Ranking: Categorical subdivisions are ranked in ascending or descending order, such as a ranking of sales performance (the *measure*) by sales persons (the *category*, with each sales person a *categorical subdivision*) during a single period.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used to show the comparison across the sales persons.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Part-to-whole: Categorical subdivisions are measured as a ratio to the whole (i.e., a percentage out of 100%).
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] A pie chart or bar chart can show the comparison of ratios, such as the market share represented by competitors in a market.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Deviation: Categorical subdivisions are compared against a reference, such as a comparison of actual vs. budget expenses for several departments of a business for a given time period.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart can show comparison of the actual versus the reference amount.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Frequency distribution: Shows the number of observations of a particular variable for given interval, such as the number of years in which the stock market return is between intervals such as 0–10%, 11–20%, etc.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] A histogram, a type of bar chart, may be used for this analysis.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] A boxplot helps visualize key statistics about the distribution, such as median, quartiles, outliers, etc.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Correlation: Comparison between observations represented by two variables (X,Y) to determine if they tend to move in the same or opposite directions.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] For example, plotting unemployment (X) and inflation (Y) for a sample of months.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] A scatter plot is typically used for this message.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Nominal comparison: Comparing categorical subdivisions in no particular order, such as the sales volume by product code.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used for this comparison.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Geographic or geospatial: Comparison of a variable across a map or layout, such as the unemployment rate by state or the number of persons on the various floors of a building.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Analysts reviewing a set of data may consider whether some or all of the messages and graphic types above are applicable to their task and audience.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The process of trial and error to identify meaningful relationships and messages in the data is part of exploratory data analysis.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] A human can distinguish differences in line length, shape, orientation, distances, and color (hue) readily without significant processing effort; these are referred to as "pre-attentive attributes".
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] For example, it may require significant time and effort ("attentive processing") to identify the number of times the digit "5" appears in a series of numbers; but if that digit is different in size, orientation, or color, instances of the digit can be noted quickly through pre-attentive processing.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Compelling graphics take advantage of pre-attentive processing and attributes and the relative strength of these attributes.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] For example, since humans can more easily process differences in line length than surface area, it may be more effective to use a bar chart (which takes advantage of line length to show comparison) rather than pie charts (which use surface area to show comparison).
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Almost all data visualizations are created for human consumption.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Knowledge of human perception and cognition is necessary when designing intuitive visualizations.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Cognition refers to processes in human beings like perception, attention, learning, memory, thought, concept formation, reading, and problem solving.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Human visual processing is efficient in detecting changes and making comparisons between quantities, sizes, shapes and variations in lightness.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] When properties of symbolic data are mapped to visual properties, humans can browse through large amounts of data efficiently.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] It is estimated that 2/3 of the brain's neurons can be involved in visual processing.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Proper visualization provides a different approach to show potential connections, relationships, etc. which are not as obvious in non-visualized quantitative data.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Visualization can become a means of data exploration.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Studies have shown individuals used on average 19% less cognitive resources, and 4.5% better able to recall details when comparing data visualization with text.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] There is no comprehensive history of data visualization.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] There are no accounts that span the entire development of visual thinking and visual representation of data, and which collate the contributions of disparate disciplines.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Michael Friendly and Daniel Denis of York University are engaged in a project that attempts to provide a comprehensive history of visualization.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is not a modern development.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Since prehistory, stellar data, or information such as location of stars were visualized on the walls of caves (such as those found in Lascaux Cave in Southern France) since the Pleistocene era.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Physical artefacts such as Mesopotamian clay tokens (5500 BC), Inca quipus (2600 BC) and Marshall Islands stick charts (n.d.) can also be considered as visualizing quantitative information.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The first documented data visualization can be tracked back to 1160 B.C. with the Turin Papyrus Map which accurately illustrates the distribution of geological resources and provides information about quarrying of those resources.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Such maps can be categorized as thematic cartography, which is a type of data visualization that presents and communicates specific data and information through a geographical illustration designed to show a particular theme connected with a specific geographic area.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Earliest documented forms of data visualization were various thematic maps from different cultures and ideograms and hieroglyphs that provided and allowed interpretation of information illustrated.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] For example, Linear B tablets of Mycenae provided a visualization of information regarding Late Bronze Age era trades in the Mediterranean.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The idea of coordinates was used by ancient Egyptian surveyors in laying out towns, earthly and heavenly positions were located by something akin to latitude and longitude at least by 200 BC, and the map projection of a spherical Earth into latitude and longitude by Claudius Ptolemy [c.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] 165] in Alexandria would serve as reference standards until the 14th century.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The invention of paper and parchment allowed further development of visualizations.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] One graph from the 10th or possibly 11th century is an illustration of planetary movements, used in an appendix of a textbook in monastery schools.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The graph apparently was meant to represent a plot of the inclinations of the planetary orbits as a function of the time.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] For this purpose, the zone of the zodiac was represented on a plane with a horizontal line divided into thirty parts as the time or longitudinal axis.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The vertical axis designates the width of the zodiac.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The horizontal scale appears to have been chosen for each planet individually for the periods cannot be reconciled.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The accompanying text refers only to the amplitudes.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The curves are apparently not related in time.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] By the 16th century, techniques and instruments for precise observation and measurement of physical quantities, and geographic and celestial position were well-developed (for example, a "wall quadrant" constructed by Tycho Brahe [1546–1601], covering an entire wall in his observatory).
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Particularly important were the development of triangulation and other methods to determine mapping locations accurately.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Very early, the measure of time led scholars to develop innovative way of visualizing the data (e.g.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Lorenz Codomann in 1596, Johannes Temporarius in 1596).
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Mathematicians René Descartes and Pierre de Fermat developed analytic geometry and two-dimensional coordinate system which heavily influenced the practical methods of displaying and calculating values.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Fermat and Blaise Pascal's work on statistics and probability theory laid the groundwork for what we now conceptualize as data.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] These developments helped William Playfair, who saw potential for graphical communication of quantitative data, to generate and develop graphical methods of statistics.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] In 1786, Playfair published the first presentation graphics.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Jacques Bertin used quantitative graphs to represent information "intuitively, clearly, accurately, and efficiently".
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] John Tukey and Edward Tufte pushed the bounds of data visualization; Tukey with his new statistical approach of exploratory data analysis and Tufte with his book "The Visual Display of Quantitative Information" paved the way for refining data visualization techniques for more than statisticians.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] With the progression of technology came the progression of data visualization; starting with hand-drawn visualizations and evolving into more technical applications – including interactive designs leading to software visualization.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The modern study of visualization started with computer graphics, which "has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] However, in its early days the lack of graphics power often limited its usefulness.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the special issue of Computer Graphics on Visualization in *Scientific Computing*.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Since then there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH".
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] They have been devoted to the general topics of data visualization, information visualization and scientific visualization, and more specific areas such as volume visualization.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Programs like SAS, SOFA, R, Minitab, Cornerstone and more allow for data visualization in the field of statistics.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Other data visualization applications, more focused and unique to individuals, programming languages such as D3, Python (through matplotlib, seaborn) and JavaScript and Java(through JavaFX) help to make the visualization of quantitative data a possibility.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Private schools have also developed programs to meet the demand for learning data visualization and associated programming libraries, including free programs like The Data Incubator or paid programs like General Assembly.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Beginning with the symposium "Data to Discovery" in 2013, ArtCenter College of Design, Caltech and JPL in Pasadena have run an annual program on interactive data visualization.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The program asks: How can interactive data visualization help scientists and engineers explore their data more effectively?
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] How can computing, design, and design thinking help maximize research results?
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] What methodologies are most effective for leveraging knowledge from these fields?
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] In recent years, with the increasing popularity of games, data and information visualization has been gradually applied in the gaming industry through the use of analytical tools to assess player statistics and game performance, which are visualized in the form of health points, maps, and diagrams.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The data is then collected and stored by developers.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The implementation of these tools in gaming assists developers in improving user experience and in the development and updating of newer games.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization involves specific terminology, some of which is derived from statistics.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The distinction between quantitative and categorical variables is important because the two types require different methods of visualization.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Two primary types of information displays are tables and graphs.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Eppler and Lengler have developed the "Periodic Table of Visualization Methods," an interactive chart displaying various data visualization methods.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] It includes six types of data visualization methods: data, information, concept, strategy, metaphor and compound.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Interactive data visualization has been a pursuit of statisticians since the late 1960s.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Examples of the developments can be found on the American Statistical Association video lending library.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] There are different approaches on the scope of data visualization.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] One common focus is on information presentation, such as Friedman (2008).
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Friendly (2008) presumes two main parts of data visualization: statistical graphics, and thematic cartography.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] All these subjects are closely related to graphic design and information representation.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Within The Harvard Business Review, Scott Berinato developed a framework to approach data visualisation.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] To start thinking visually, users must consider two questions; 1) What you have and 2) what you're doing.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] The first step is identifying what data you want visualised.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] It is data-driven like profit over the past ten years or a conceptual idea like how a specific organisation is structured.
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Once this question is answered one can then focus on whether they are trying to communicate information (declarative visualisation) or trying to figure something out (exploratory visualisation).
[src:umap-embedding/data-visualization-p01] Scott Berinato combines these questions to give four types of visual communication that each have their own goals.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Methods are commonly divided into linear and nonlinear approaches.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Linear approaches can be further divided into feature selection and feature extraction.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Dimensionality reduction can be used for noise reduction, data visualization, cluster analysis, or as an intermediate step to facilitate other analyses.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The process of feature selection aims to find a suitable subset of the input variables (*features*, or *attributes*) for the task at hand.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The three strategies are: the *filter* strategy (e.g., information gain), the *wrapper* strategy (e.g., accuracy-guided search), and the *embedded* strategy (features are added or removed while building the model based on prediction errors).
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Data analysis such as regression or classification can be done in the reduced space more accurately than in the original space.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Feature projection (also called feature extraction) transforms the data from the high-dimensional space to a space of fewer dimensions.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The data transformation may be linear, as in principal component analysis (PCA), but many nonlinear dimensionality reduction techniques also exist.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] For multidimensional data, tensor representation can be used in dimensionality reduction through multilinear subspace learning.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The main linear technique for dimensionality reduction, principal component analysis, performs a linear mapping of the data to a lower-dimensional space in such a way that the variance of the data in the low-dimensional representation is maximized.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] In practice, the covariance (and sometimes the correlation) matrix of the data is constructed and the eigenvectors on this matrix are computed.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The eigenvectors that correspond to the largest eigenvalues (the principal components) can now be used to reconstruct a large fraction of the variance of the original data.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Moreover, the first few eigenvectors can often be interpreted in terms of the large-scale physical behavior of the system, because they often contribute the vast majority of the system's energy, especially in low-dimensional systems.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Still, this must be proved on a case-by-case basis as not all systems exhibit this behavior.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The original space (with dimension of the number of points) has been reduced (with data loss, but hopefully retaining the most important variance) to the space spanned by a few eigenvectors.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] NMF decomposes a non-negative matrix to the product of two non-negative ones, which has been a promising tool in fields where only non-negative signals exist, such as astronomy.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] With a stable component basis during construction, and a linear modeling process, sequential NMF is able to preserve the flux in direct imaging of circumstellar structures in astronomy, as one of the methods of detecting exoplanets, especially for the direct imaging of circumstellar discs.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] In comparison with PCA, NMF does not remove the mean of the matrices, which leads to physical non-negative fluxes; therefore NMF is able to preserve more information than PCA as demonstrated by Ren et al.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Principal component analysis can be employed in a nonlinear way by means of the kernel trick.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The resulting technique is capable of constructing nonlinear mappings that maximize the variance in the data.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The resulting technique is called kernel PCA.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Other prominent nonlinear techniques include manifold learning techniques such as Isomap, locally linear embedding (LLE), Hessian LLE, Laplacian eigenmaps, and methods based on tangent space analysis.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] More recently, techniques have been proposed that, instead of defining a fixed kernel, try to learn the kernel using semidefinite programming.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The most prominent example of such a technique is maximum variance unfolding (MVU).
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The central idea of MVU is to exactly preserve all pairwise distances between nearest neighbors (in the inner product space) while maximizing the distances between points that are not nearest neighbors.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] An alternative approach to neighborhood preservation is through the minimization of a cost function that measures differences between distances in the input and output spaces.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] A different approach to nonlinear dimensionality reduction is through the use of autoencoders, a special kind of feedforward neural networks with a bottleneck hidden layer.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The training of deep encoders is typically performed using a greedy layer-wise pre-training (e.g., using a stack of restricted Boltzmann machines) that is followed by a finetuning stage based on backpropagation.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Linear discriminant analysis (LDA) is a generalization of Fisher's linear discriminant, a method used in statistics, pattern recognition, and machine learning to find a linear combination of features that characterizes or separates two or more classes of objects or events.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] GDA deals with nonlinear discriminant analysis using kernel function operator.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] The underlying theory is close to the support-vector machines (SVM) insofar as the GDA method provides a mapping of the input vectors into high-dimensional feature space.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Similar to LDA, the objective of GDA is to find a projection for the features into a lower dimensional space by maximizing the ratio of between-class scatter to within-class scatter.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Autoencoders can be used to learn nonlinear dimension reduction functions and codings together with an inverse function from the coding to the original representation.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] T-distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding (t-SNE) is a nonlinear dimensionality reduction technique useful for the visualization of high-dimensional datasets.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] It is not recommended for use in analysis such as clustering or outlier detection since it does not necessarily preserve densities or distances well.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Uniform manifold approximation and projection (UMAP) is a nonlinear dimensionality reduction technique.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] Visually, it is similar to t-SNE, but it assumes that the data is uniformly distributed on a locally connected Riemannian manifold and that the Riemannian metric is locally constant or approximately locally constant.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] For high-dimensional datasets, dimension reduction is usually performed prior to applying a *k*-nearest neighbors (*k*-NN) algorithm in order to mitigate the curse of dimensionality.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] In machine learning, this process is also called low-dimensional embedding.
[src:umap-embedding/dimensionality-reduction] A dimensionality reduction technique that is sometimes used in neuroscience is maximally informative dimensions, which finds a lower-dimensional representation of a dataset such that as much information as possible about the original data is preserved.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] High dimensional data can be hard for machines to work with, requiring significant time and space for analysis.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] It also presents a challenge for humans, since it's hard to visualize or understand data in more than three dimensions.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Reducing the dimensionality of a data set, while keeping its essential features relatively intact, can make algorithms more efficient and allow analysts to visualize trends and patterns.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The reduced-dimensional representations of data are often referred to as "intrinsic variables".
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] This description implies that these are the values from which the data was produced.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] For example, consider a dataset that contains images of a letter 'A', which has been scaled and rotated by varying amounts.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Each image can be represented as a vector of 1024 pixel values.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Each row is a sample on a two-dimensional manifold in 1024-dimensional space (a Hamming space).
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The intrinsic dimensionality is two, because two variables (rotation and scale) were varied in order to produce the data.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Information about the shape or look of a letter 'A' is not part of the intrinsic variables because it is the same in every instance.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Nonlinear dimensionality reduction will discard the correlated information (the letter 'A') and recover only the varying information (rotation and scale).
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] By comparison, if principal component analysis, which is a linear dimensionality reduction algorithm, is used to reduce this same dataset into two dimensions, the resulting values are not so well organized.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] This demonstrates that the high-dimensional vectors (each representing a letter 'A') that sample this manifold vary in a non-linear manner.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] It should be apparent, therefore, that NLDR has several applications in the field of computer-vision.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] For example, consider a robot that uses a camera to navigate in a closed static environment.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The images obtained by that camera can be considered to be samples on a manifold in high-dimensional space, and the intrinsic variables of that manifold will represent the robot's position and orientation.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Invariant manifolds are of general interest for model order reduction in dynamical systems.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] In particular, if there is an attracting invariant manifold in the phase space, nearby trajectories will converge onto it and stay on it indefinitely, rendering it a candidate for dimensionality reduction of the dynamical system.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] While such manifolds are not guaranteed to exist in general, the theory of spectral submanifolds (SSM) gives conditions for the existence of unique attracting invariant objects in a broad class of dynamical systems.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Active research in NLDR seeks to unfold the observation manifolds associated with dynamical systems to develop modeling techniques.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Some of the more prominent **nonlinear dimensionality reduction** techniques are listed below.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Sammon's mapping is one of the first and most popular NLDR techniques.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The self-organizing map (SOM, also called *Kohonen map*) and its probabilistic variant generative topographic mapping (GTM) use a point representation in the embedded space to form a latent variable model based on a non-linear mapping from the embedded space to the high-dimensional space.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] These techniques are related to work on density networks, which also are based around the same probabilistic model.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Perhaps the most widely used algorithm for dimensional reduction is kernel PCA.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] It then projects the data onto the first *k* eigenvectors of that matrix.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] It then projects the transformed data onto the first *k* eigenvectors of that matrix, just like PCA.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] It uses the kernel trick to factor away much of the computation, such that the entire process can be performed without actually computing $\Phi (\mathbf {x} )$ .
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Of course $\Phi$ must be chosen such that it has a known corresponding kernel.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Unfortunately, it is not trivial to find a good kernel for a given problem, so KPCA does not yield good results with some problems when using standard kernels.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] For example, it is known to perform poorly with these kernels on the Swiss roll manifold.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] However, one can view certain other methods that perform well in such settings (e.g., Laplacian Eigenmaps, LLE) as special cases of kernel PCA by constructing a data-dependent kernel matrix.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] KPCA has an internal model, so it can be used to map points onto its embedding that were not available at training time.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Laplacian eigenmaps uses spectral techniques to perform dimensionality reduction.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] This technique relies on the basic assumption that the data lies in a low-dimensional manifold in a high-dimensional space.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] This algorithm cannot embed out-of-sample points, but techniques based on Reproducing kernel Hilbert space regularization exist for adding this capability.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Such techniques can be applied to other nonlinear dimensionality reduction algorithms as well.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Traditional techniques like principal component analysis do not consider the intrinsic geometry of the data.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Laplacian eigenmaps builds a graph from neighborhood information of the data set.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Each data point serves as a node on the graph and connectivity between nodes is governed by the proximity of neighboring points (using e.g. the k-nearest neighbor algorithm).
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The graph thus generated can be considered as a discrete approximation of the low-dimensional manifold in the high-dimensional space.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Minimization of a cost function based on the graph ensures that points close to each other on the manifold are mapped close to each other in the low-dimensional space, preserving local distances.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The eigenfunctions of the Laplace–Beltrami operator on the manifold serve as the embedding dimensions, since under mild conditions this operator has a countable spectrum that is a basis for square integrable functions on the manifold (compare to Fourier series on the unit circle manifold).
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Attempts to place Laplacian eigenmaps on solid theoretical ground have met with some success, as under certain nonrestrictive assumptions, the graph Laplacian matrix has been shown to converge to the Laplace–Beltrami operator as the number of points goes to infinity.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Isomap is a combination of the Floyd–Warshall algorithm with classic Multidimensional Scaling (MDS).
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Classic MDS takes a matrix of pair-wise distances between all points and computes a position for each point.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Isomap assumes that the pair-wise distances are only known between neighboring points, and uses the Floyd–Warshall algorithm to compute the pair-wise distances between all other points.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] This effectively estimates the full matrix of pair-wise geodesic distances between all of the points.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Isomap then uses classic MDS to compute the reduced-dimensional positions of all the points.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Landmark-Isomap is a variant of this algorithm that uses landmarks to increase speed, at the cost of some accuracy.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] In manifold learning, the input data is assumed to be sampled from a low dimensional manifold that is embedded inside of a higher-dimensional vector space.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The main intuition behind MVU is to exploit the local linearity of manifolds and create a mapping that preserves local neighbourhoods at every point of the underlying manifold.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Locally-linear Embedding (LLE) was presented at approximately the same time as Isomap.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] It has several advantages over Isomap, including faster optimization when implemented to take advantage of sparse matrix algorithms, and better results with many problems.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] LLE also begins by finding a set of the nearest neighbors of each point.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] It then computes a set of weights for each point that best describes the point as a linear combination of its neighbors.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Finally, it uses an eigenvector-based optimization technique to find the low-dimensional embedding of points, such that each point is still described with the same linear combination of its neighbors.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] LLE tends to handle non-uniform sample densities poorly because there is no fixed unit to prevent the weights from drifting as various regions differ in sample densities.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The original data points $X_{i}\in \mathbb {R} ^{D}$ , and the goal of LLE is to embed each point $X_{i}$ to some low-dimensional point $Y_{i}\in \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , where $d\ll D$ .
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] In the **first** step, it computes, for each point *X**i*, the best approximation of *X**i* based on barycentric coordinates of its neighbors *X**j*.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The original point is approximately reconstructed by a linear combination, given by the weight matrix *W**ij*, of its neighbors.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The weights *W**ij* refer to the amount of contribution the point *X**j* has while reconstructing the point *X**i*.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] These two constraints ensure that W is unaffected by rotation and translation.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] In the **second** step, a neighborhood preserving map is created based the weights.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Unlike in the previous cost function, the weights Wij are kept fixed and the minimization is done on the points Yi to optimize the coordinates.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] This minimization problem can be solved by solving a sparse *N* X *N* eigenvalue problem (*N* being the number of data points), whose bottom *d* nonzero eigen vectors provide an orthogonal set of coordinates.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The only hyperparameter in the algorithm is what counts as a "neighbor" of a point.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Generally the data points are reconstructed from *K* nearest neighbors, as measured by Euclidean distance.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] In this case, the algorithm has only one integer-valued hyperparameter *K,* which can be chosen by cross validation.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Like LLE, Hessian LLE is also based on sparse matrix techniques.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] It tends to yield results of a much higher quality than LLE.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Unfortunately, it has a very costly computational complexity, so it is not well-suited for heavily sampled manifolds.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Modified LLE (MLLE) is another LLE variant which uses multiple weights in each neighborhood to address the local weight matrix conditioning problem which leads to distortions in LLE maps.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Loosely speaking the multiple weights are the local orthogonal projection of the original weights produced by LLE.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The theoretical and empirical implications from the correct application of this algorithm are far-reaching.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] LTSA is based on the intuition that when a manifold is correctly unfolded, all of the tangent hyperplanes to the manifold will become aligned.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] It begins by computing the *k*-nearest neighbors of every point.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] It computes the tangent space at every point by computing the *d*-first principal components in each local neighborhood.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] It then optimizes to find an embedding that aligns the tangent spaces.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Maximum Variance Unfolding, Isomap and Locally Linear Embedding share a common intuition relying on the notion that if a manifold is properly unfolded, then variance over the points is maximized.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Its initial step, like Isomap and Locally Linear Embedding, is finding the *k*-nearest neighbors of every point.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] It then seeks to solve the problem of maximizing the distance between all non-neighboring points, constrained such that the distances between neighboring points are preserved.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The primary contribution of this algorithm is a technique for casting this problem as a semidefinite programming problem.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Unfortunately, semidefinite programming solvers have a high computational cost.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Like Locally Linear Embedding, it has no internal model.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] An autoencoder is a feed-forward neural network which is trained to approximate the identity function.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] That is, it is trained to map from a vector of values to the same vector.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] When used for dimensionality reduction purposes, one of the hidden layers in the network is limited to contain only a small number of network units.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Thus, the network must learn to encode the vector into a small number of dimensions and then decode it back into the original space.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Thus, the first half of the network is a model which maps from high to low-dimensional space, and the second half maps from low to high-dimensional space.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Although the idea of autoencoders is quite old, training of deep autoencoders has only recently become possible through the use of restricted Boltzmann machines and stacked denoising autoencoders.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Related to autoencoders is the NeuroScale algorithm, which uses stress functions inspired by multidimensional scaling and Sammon mappings (see above) to learn a non-linear mapping from the high-dimensional to the embedded space.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The mappings in NeuroScale are based on radial basis function networks.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Gaussian process latent variable models (GPLVM) are probabilistic dimensionality reduction methods that use Gaussian Processes (GPs) to find a lower dimensional non-linear embedding of high dimensional data.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] They are an extension of the Probabilistic formulation of PCA.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The model is defined probabilistically and the latent variables are then marginalized and parameters are obtained by maximizing the likelihood.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Like kernel PCA they use a kernel function to form a non linear mapping (in the form of a Gaussian process).
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] However, in the GPLVM the mapping is from the embedded(latent) space to the data space (like density networks and GTM) whereas in kernel PCA it is in the opposite direction.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] It was originally proposed for visualization of high dimensional data but has been extended to construct a shared manifold model between two observation spaces.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] GPLVM and its many variants have been proposed specially for human motion modeling, e.g., back constrained GPLVM, GP dynamic model (GPDM), balanced GPDM (B-GPDM) and topologically constrained GPDM.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] To capture the coupling effect of the pose and gait manifolds in the gait analysis, a multi-layer joint gait-pose manifolds was proposed.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Relational perspective map is a multidimensional scaling algorithm.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The algorithm finds a configuration of data points on a manifold by simulating a multi-particle dynamic system on a closed manifold, where data points are mapped to particles and distances (or dissimilarity) between data points represent a repulsive force.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] As the manifold gradually grows in size the multi-particle system cools down gradually and converges to a configuration that reflects the distance information of the data points.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Relational perspective map was inspired by a physical model in which positively charged particles move freely on the surface of a ball.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Guided by the Coulomb force between particles, the minimal energy configuration of the particles will reflect the strength of repulsive forces between the particles.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The Relational perspective map was introduced in.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The algorithm firstly used the flat torus as the image manifold, then it has been extended (in the software VisuMap to use other types of closed manifolds, like the sphere, projective space, and Klein bottle, as image manifolds.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Contagion maps use multiple contagions on a network to map the nodes as a point cloud.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] In the case of the Global cascades model the speed of the spread can be adjusted with the threshold parameter $t\in [0,1]$ .
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] For $t=0$ the contagion map is equivalent to the Isomap algorithm.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Curvilinear component analysis (CCA) looks for the configuration of points in the output space that preserves original distances as much as possible while focusing on small distances in the output space (conversely to Sammon's mapping which focus on small distances in original space).
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] It should be noticed that CCA, as an iterative learning algorithm, actually starts with focus on large distances (like the Sammon algorithm), then gradually change focus to small distances.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The small distance information will overwrite the large distance information, if compromises between the two have to be made.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The stress function of CCA is related to a sum of right Bregman divergences.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] CDA trains a self-organizing neural network to fit the manifold and seeks to preserve geodesic distances in its embedding.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] It is based on Curvilinear Component Analysis (which extended Sammon's mapping), but uses geodesic distances instead.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Diffeomorphic Dimensionality Reduction or *Diffeomap* learns a smooth diffeomorphic mapping which transports the data onto a lower-dimensional linear subspace.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The methods solves for a smooth time indexed vector field such that flows along the field which start at the data points will end at a lower-dimensional linear subspace, thereby attempting to preserve pairwise differences under both the forward and inverse mapping.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Manifold alignment takes advantage of the assumption that disparate data sets produced by similar generating processes will share a similar underlying manifold representation.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] By learning projections from each original space to the shared manifold, correspondences are recovered and knowledge from one domain can be transferred to another.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Most manifold alignment techniques consider only two data sets, but the concept extends to arbitrarily many initial data sets.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Diffusion maps leverages the relationship between heat diffusion and a random walk (Markov Chain); an analogy is drawn between the diffusion operator on a manifold and a Markov transition matrix operating on functions defined on the graph whose nodes were sampled from the manifold.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] In particular, let a data set be represented by $\mathbf {X} =[x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{n}]\in \Omega \subset \mathbf {R^{D}}$ .
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The underlying assumption of diffusion map is that the high-dimensional data lies on a low-dimensional manifold of dimension $\mathbf {d}$ .
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Let **X** represent the data set and $\mu$ represent the distribution of the data points on **X**.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Further, define a **kernel** which represents some notion of affinity of the points in **X**.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Thus one can think of the individual data points as the nodes of a graph and the kernel *k* as defining some sort of affinity on that graph.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The graph is symmetric by construction since the kernel is symmetric.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] It is easy to see here that from the tuple (**X**,**k**) one can construct a reversible Markov Chain.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] This technique is common to a variety of fields and is known as the graph Laplacian.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] For example, the graph **K** = (*X*,*E*) can be constructed using a Gaussian kernel.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] In the above equation, $x_{i}\sim x_{j}$ denotes that $x_{i}$ is a nearest neighbor of $x_{j}$ .
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Properly, Geodesic distance should be used to actually measure distances on the manifold.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Since the exact structure of the manifold is not available, for the nearest neighbors the geodesic distance is approximated by euclidean distance.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The former means that very little diffusion has taken place while the latter implies that the diffusion process is nearly complete.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Different strategies to choose $\sigma$ can be found in.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] P now represents a Markov chain. $P(x_{i},x_{j})$ is the probability of transitioning from $x_{i}$ to $x_{j}$ in one time step.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Similarly the probability of transitioning from $x_{i}$ to $x_{j}$ in **t** time steps is given by $P^{t}(x_{i},x_{j})$ .
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Here $P^{t}$ is the matrix P multiplied by itself **t** times.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The Markov matrix P constitutes some notion of local geometry of the data set **X**.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The major difference between diffusion maps and principal component analysis is that only local features of the data are considered in diffusion maps as opposed to taking correlations of the entire data set.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] K defines a random walk on the data set which means that the kernel captures some local geometry of data set.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The Markov chain defines fast and slow directions of propagation through the kernel values.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] As the walk propagates forward in time, the local geometry information aggregates in the same way as local transitions (defined by differential equations) of the dynamical system.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] For fixed t, $D_{t}$ defines a distance between any two points of the data set based on path connectivity: the value of $D_{t}(x,y)$ will be smaller the more paths that connect **x** to **y** and vice versa.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Local Multidimensional Scaling performs multidimensional scaling in local regions, and then uses convex optimization to fit all the pieces together.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Nonlinear PCA (NLPCA) uses backpropagation to train a multi-layer perceptron (MLP) to fit to a manifold.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Unlike typical MLP training, which only updates the weights, NLPCA updates both the weights and the inputs.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] That is, both the weights and inputs are treated as latent values.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] After training, the latent inputs are a low-dimensional representation of the observed vectors, and the MLP maps from that low-dimensional representation to the high-dimensional observation space.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Manifold Sculpting uses graduated optimization to find an embedding.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Like other algorithms, it computes the *k*-nearest neighbors and tries to seek an embedding that preserves relationships in local neighborhoods.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] It slowly scales variance out of higher dimensions, while simultaneously adjusting points in lower dimensions to preserve those relationships.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] If the rate of scaling is small, it can find very precise embeddings.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] It boasts higher empirical accuracy than other algorithms with several problems.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] It can also be used to refine the results from other manifold learning algorithms.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] It struggles to unfold some manifolds, however, unless a very slow scaling rate is used.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] RankVisu is designed to preserve rank of neighborhood rather than distance.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] RankVisu is especially useful on difficult tasks (when the preservation of distance cannot be achieved satisfyingly).
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Indeed, the rank of neighborhood is less informative than distance (ranks can be deduced from distances but distances cannot be deduced from ranks) and its preservation is thus easier.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Topologically constrained isometric embedding (TCIE) is an algorithm based on approximating geodesic distances after filtering geodesics inconsistent with the Euclidean metric.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] Aimed at correcting the distortions caused when Isomap is used to map intrinsically non-convex data, TCIE uses weight least-squares MDS in order to obtain a more accurate mapping.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The TCIE algorithm first detects possible boundary points in the data, and during computation of the geodesic length marks inconsistent geodesics, to be given a small weight in the weighted stress majorization that follows.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] t-distributed stochastic neighbor embedding (t-SNE) is widely used.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] It is one of a family of stochastic neighbor embedding methods.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The algorithm computes the probability that pairs of datapoints in the high-dimensional space are related, and then chooses low-dimensional embeddings which produce a similar distribution.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] It works in a similar fashion as the t-SNE, with the main difference being the inclusion of a repulsive term to move far points away from each other.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] A method based on proximity matrices is one where the data is presented to the algorithm in the form of a similarity matrix or a distance matrix.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] These methods all fall under the broader class of metric multidimensional scaling.
[src:umap-embedding/manifold-learning] The variations tend to be differences in how the proximity data is computed; for example, isomap, locally linear embeddings, maximum variance unfolding, and Sammon mapping (which is not in fact a mapping) are examples of metric multidimensional scaling methods.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] The **nearest neighbor graph** (**NNG**) is a directed graph defined for a set of points in a metric space, such as the Euclidean distance in the plane.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] The NNG has a vertex for each point, and a directed edge from *p* to *q* whenever *q* is a nearest neighbor of *p*, a point whose distance from *p* is minimum among all the given points other than *p* itself.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] In many uses of these graphs, the directions of the edges are ignored and the NNG is defined instead as an undirected graph.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] However, the nearest neighbor relation is not a symmetric one, i.e., *p* from the definition is not necessarily a nearest neighbor for *q*.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] In theoretical discussions of algorithms a kind of general position is often assumed, namely, the nearest (k-nearest) neighbor is unique for each object.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] In implementations of the algorithms it is necessary to bear in mind that this is not always the case.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] For situations in which it is necessary to make the nearest neighbor for each object unique, the set *P* may be indexed and in the case of a tie the object with, e.g., the largest index may be taken as the nearest neighbor.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] The ***k*-nearest neighbors graph** (***k*-NNG**) is a graph in which two vertices *p* and *q* are connected by an edge, if the distance between *p* and *q* is among the *k*-th smallest distances from *p* to other objects from *P*.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] The NNG is a special case of the *k*-NNG, namely it is the 1-NNG.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] *k*-NNGs obey a separator theorem: they can be partitioned into two subgraphs of at most *n*(*d* + 1)/(*d* + 2) vertices each by the removal of O(*k*1/*d**n*1 − 1/*d*) points.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] A *k*-NNG can be approximated using an efficient algorithm with 90% recall that is faster than a brute-force search by an order of magnitude.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] Another variation is the **farthest neighbor graph** (FNG), in which each point is connected by an edge to the farthest point from it, instead of the nearest point.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] NNGs for points in the plane as well as in multidimensional spaces find applications, e.g., in data compression, motion planning, and facilities location.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] In statistical analysis, the nearest-neighbor chain algorithm based on following paths in this graph can be used to find hierarchical clusterings quickly.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] Nearest neighbor graphs are also a subject of computational geometry.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] The method can be used to induce a graph on nodes with unknown connectivity.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] For a set of points on a line, the nearest neighbor of a point is its left or right (or both) neighbor, if they are sorted along the line.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] Therefore, the NNG is a path or a forest of several paths and may be constructed in O(*n* log *n*) time by sorting.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] This estimate is asymptotically optimal for certain models of computation, because the constructed NNG gives the answer to the element uniqueness problem: it is sufficient to check whether the NNG has a zero-length edge.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] Unless stated otherwise, it is assumed that the NNGs are digraphs with uniquely defined nearest neighbors as described in the introduction.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] Only cycles of length 2 are possible in an NNG and each weakly connected component of an NNG with at least 2 vertices has exactly one 2-cycle.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] For the points in the plane the NNG is a planar graph with vertex degrees at most 6.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] If points are in general position, the degree is at most 5.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] The NNG (treated as an undirected graph with multiple nearest neighbors allowed) of a set of points in the plane or any higher dimension is a subgraph of the Delaunay triangulation, the Gabriel graph, and the Semi-Yao graph.
[src:umap-embedding/nearest-neighbor-graph] If the points are in general position or if the single nearest neighbor condition is imposed, the NNG is a forest, a subgraph of the Euclidean minimum spanning tree.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] In applied mathematics, **topological data analysis** (**TDA**) is an approach to the analysis of datasets using techniques from topology.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Extraction of information from datasets that are high-dimensional, incomplete and noisy is generally challenging.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] TDA provides a general framework to analyze such data in a manner that is insensitive to the particular metric chosen and provides dimensionality reduction and robustness to noise.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Beyond this, it inherits functoriality, a fundamental concept of modern mathematics, from its topological nature, which allows it to adapt to new mathematical tools.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The initial motivation is to study the shape of data.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] TDA has combined algebraic topology and other tools from pure mathematics to allow mathematically rigorous study of "shape".
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The main tool is persistent homology, an adaptation of homology to point cloud data.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Persistent homology has been applied to many types of data across many fields.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Moreover, its mathematical foundation is also of theoretical importance.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The unique features of TDA make it a promising bridge between topology and geometry.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] TDA is premised on the idea that the shape of data sets contains relevant information.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Real high-dimensional data is typically sparse, and tends to have relevant low dimensional features.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] One task of TDA is to provide a precise characterization of this fact.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] For example, the trajectory of a simple predator-prey system governed by the Lotka–Volterra equations forms a closed circle in state space.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] TDA provides tools to detect and quantify such recurrent motion.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Many algorithms for data analysis, including those used in TDA, require setting various parameters.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Without prior domain knowledge, the correct collection of parameters for a data set is difficult to choose.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The main insight of persistent homology is to use the information obtained from all parameter values by encoding this huge amount of information into an understandable and easy-to-represent form.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] With TDA, there is a mathematical interpretation when the information is a homology group.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] In general, the assumption is that features that persist for a wide range of parameters are "true" features.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Features persisting for only a narrow range of parameters are presumed to be noise, although the theoretical justification for this is unclear.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Precursors to the full concept of persistent homology appeared gradually over time.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] In 1990, Patrizio Frosini introduced a pseudo-distance between submanifolds, and later the size function, which on 1-dim curves is equivalent to the 0th persistent homology.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Nearly a decade later, Vanessa Robins studied the images of homomorphisms induced by inclusion.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Finally, shortly thereafter, Herbert Edelsbrunner et al. introduced the concept of persistent homology together with an efficient algorithm and its visualization as a persistence diagram.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Gunnar Carlsson et al. reformulated the initial definition and gave an equivalent visualization method called persistence barcodes, interpreting persistence in the language of commutative algebra.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] In algebraic topology the persistent homology has emerged through the work of Sergey Barannikov on Morse theory.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Some widely used concepts are introduced below.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Note that some definitions may vary from author to author.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] A **point cloud** is often defined as a finite set of points in some Euclidean space, but may be taken to be any finite metric space.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The **Čech complex** of a point cloud is the *nerve* of the *cover* of balls of a fixed radius around each point in the cloud.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The **persistent homology group** $PH$ of a point cloud is the persistence module defined as $PH_{k}(X)=\prod H_{k}(X_{r})$ , where $X_{r}$ is the Čech complex of radius r of the point cloud X and $H_{k}$ is the homology group.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] A **persistence barcode** is a multiset of intervals in $\mathbb {R}$ , and a **persistence diagram** is a multiset of points in $\Delta$ ( $:=\{(u,v)\in \mathbb {R} ^{2}\mid u,v\geq 0,u\leq v\}$ ).
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The **Wasserstein distance** between two persistence diagrams X and Y is defined as $W_{p}[L_{q}](X,Y):=\inf _{\varphi :X\to Y}\left[\sum _{x\in X}(\Vert x-\varphi (x)\Vert _{q})^{p}\right]^{1/p}$ where $1\leq p,q\leq \infty$ and $\varphi$ ranges over bijections between X and Y .
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Please refer to figure 3.1 in Munch for illustration.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The **bottleneck distance** between X and Y is $W_{\infty }[L_{q}](X,Y):=\inf _{\varphi :X\to Y}\sup _{x\in X}\Vert x-\varphi (x)\Vert _{q}.$ This is a special case of Wasserstein distance, letting $p=\infty$ .
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The first classification theorem for persistent homology appeared in 1994 via Barannikov's canonical forms.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Persistent homology is visualized through a barcode or persistence diagram.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The barcode has its root in abstract mathematics.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Namely, the category of finite filtered complexes over a field is semi-simple.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Any filtered complex is isomorphic to its canonical form, a direct sum of one- and two-dimensional simple filtered complexes.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Stability is desirable because it provides robustness against noise.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The first algorithm over all fields for persistent homology in algebraic topology setting was described by Barannikov through reduction to the canonical form by upper-triangular matrices.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The algorithm for persistent homology over $F_{2}$ was given by Edelsbrunner et al.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Afra Zomorodian and Carlsson gave the practical algorithm to compute persistent homology over all fields.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Edelsbrunner and Harer's book gives general guidance on computational topology.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] One issue that arises in computation is the choice of complex.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The Čech complex and the Vietoris–Rips complex are most natural at first glance; however, their size grows rapidly with the number of data points.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The Vietoris–Rips complex is preferred over the Čech complex because its definition is simpler and the Čech complex requires extra effort to define in a general finite metric space.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Efficient ways to lower the computational cost of homology have been studied.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] For example, the α-complex and witness complex are used to reduce the dimension and size of complexes.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Recently, Discrete Morse theory has shown promise for computational homology because it can reduce a given simplicial complex to a much smaller cellular complex which is homotopic to the original one.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] This reduction can in fact be performed as the complex is constructed by using matroid theory, leading to further performance increases.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Another recent algorithm saves time by ignoring the homology classes with low persistence.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Various software packages are available, such as javaPlex, Dionysus, Perseus, PHAT, DIPHA, GUDHI, Ripser, and TDAstats.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] A comparison between these tools is done by Otter et al.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Giotto-tda is a Python package dedicated to integrating TDA in the machine learning workflow by means of a scikit-learn [1] API.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] An R package TDA is capable of calculating recently invented concepts like landscape and the kernel distance estimator.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The Topology ToolKit is specialized for continuous data defined on manifolds of low dimension (1, 2 or 3), as typically found in scientific visualization.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Cubicle is optimized for large (gigabyte-scale) grayscale image data in dimension 1, 2 or 3 using cubical complexes and discrete Morse theory.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Another R package, TDAstats, uses the Ripser library to calculate persistent homology.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] High-dimensional data is impossible to visualize directly.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Many methods have been invented to extract a low-dimensional structure from the data set, such as principal component analysis and multidimensional scaling.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] However, it is important to note that the problem itself is ill-posed, since many different topological features can be found in the same data set.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Thus, the study of visualization of high-dimensional spaces is of central importance to TDA, although it does not necessarily involve the use of persistent homology.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] However, recent attempts have been made to use persistent homology in data visualization.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Carlsson et al. have proposed a general method called **MAPPER**.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] It inherits the idea of Jean-Pierre Serre that a covering preserves homotopy.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Let X and Z be topological spaces and let $f\colon X\to Z$ be a continuous map.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Let $\mathbb {U} =\{U_{\alpha }\}_{\alpha \in A}$ be a finite open covering of Z .
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The output of MAPPER is the nerve of the pullback cover ${\textstyle M(\mathbb {U} ,f):=N(f^{-1}(\mathbb {U} ))}$ , where each preimage is split into its connected components.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] This is a very general concept, of which the Reeb graph and merge trees are special cases.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] This is not quite the original definition.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Carlsson et al. choose Z to be $\mathbb {R}$ or $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ , and cover it with open sets such that at most two intersect.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] This restriction means that the output is in the form of a complex network.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Because the topology of a finite point cloud is trivial, clustering methods (such as single linkage) are used to produce the analogue of connected sets in the preimage $f^{-1}(U)$ when MAPPER is applied to actual data.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Mathematically speaking, MAPPER is a variation of the Reeb graph.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] One problem is instability, in that some change of the choice of the cover can lead to major change of the output of the algorithm.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Work has been done to overcome this problem.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Three successful applications of MAPPER can be found in Carlsson et al.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] A comment on the applications in this paper by J.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Curry is that "a common feature of interest in applications is the presence of flares or tendrils".
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] A free implementation of MAPPER written by Daniel Müllner and Aravindakshan Babu is available online.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] MAPPER also forms the basis of Ayasdi's AI platform.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Multidimensional persistence is important to TDA.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The concept arises in both theory and practice.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The first investigation of multidimensional persistence was early in the development of TDA.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Carlsson-Zomorodian introduced the theory of multidimensional persistence in and in collaboration with Singh introduced the use of tools from symbolic algebra (Gröbner basis methods) to compute MPH modules.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Their definition presents multidimensional persistence with n parameters as a $\mathbb {Z} ^{n}$ graded module over a polynomial ring in n variables.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Tools from commutative and homological algebra are applied to the study of multidimensional persistence in work of Harrington-Otter-Schenck-Tillman.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The first application to appear in the literature is a method for shape comparison, similar to the invention of TDA.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] It might be worth noting that there are controversies on the definition of multidimensional persistence.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] One of the advantages of one-dimensional persistence is its representability by a diagram or barcode.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] However, discrete complete invariants of multidimensional persistence modules do not exist.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Nonetheless, many results have been established.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Carlsson and Zomorodian introduced the **rank invariant** $\rho _{M}(u,v)$ , defined as the $\rho _{M}(u,v)=\mathrm {rank} (x^{u-v}\colon M_{u}\to M_{v})$ , in which M is a finitely generated n-graded module.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] In one dimension, it is equivalent to the barcode.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] In the literature, the rank invariant is often referred as the persistent Betti numbers (PBNs).
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] In many theoretical works, authors have used a more restricted definition, an analogue from sublevel set persistence.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Some basic properties include monotonicity and diagonal jump.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Persistent Betti numbers will be finite if X is a compact and locally contractible subspace of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Using a foliation method, the k-dim PBNs can be decomposed into a family of 1-dim PBNs by dimensionality deduction.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] This method has also led to a proof that multi-dim PBNs are stable.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The discontinuities of PBNs only occur at points $(u,v)(u\leq v)$ where either u is a discontinuous point of $\rho _{M}(\star ,v)$ or v is a discontinuous point of $\rho (u,\star )$ under the assumption that $f\in C^{0}(X,\mathbb {R} ^{k})$ and X is a compact, triangulable topological space.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Persistent space, a generalization of persistent diagram, is defined as the multiset of all points with multiplicity larger than 0 and the diagonal.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] It provides a stable and complete representation of PBNs.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] An ongoing work by Carlsson et al. is trying to give geometric interpretation of persistent homology, which might provide insights on how to combine machine learning theory with topological data analysis.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The first practical algorithm to compute multidimensional persistence was invented very early.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] After then, many other algorithms have been proposed, based on such concepts as discrete morse theory and finite sample estimating.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The standard paradigm in TDA is often referred as **sublevel persistence**.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Apart from multidimensional persistence, many works have been done to extend this special case.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The nonzero maps in persistence module are restricted by the preorder relationship in the category.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] However, mathematicians have found that the unanimity of direction is not essential to many results.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] "The philosophical point is that the decomposition theory of graph representations is somewhat independent of the orientation of the graph edges".
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Zigzag persistence is important to the theoretical side.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The examples given in Carlsson's review paper to illustrate the importance of functorality all share some of its features.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] There are some attempts to loosen the stricter restriction of the function.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Please refer to the Categorification and cosheaves and Impact on mathematics sections for more information.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] It's natural to extend persistence homology to other basic concepts in algebraic topology, such as cohomology and relative homology/cohomology.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] An interesting application is the computation of circular coordinates for a data set via the first persistent cohomology group.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Normal persistence homology studies real-valued functions.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The circle-valued map might be useful, "persistence theory for circle-valued maps promises to play the role for some vector fields as does the standard persistence theory for scalar fields", as commented in Dan Burghelea et al.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The main difference is that Jordan cells (very similar in format to the Jordan blocks in linear algebra) are nontrivial in circle-valued functions, which would be zero in real-valued case, and combining with barcodes give the invariants of a tame map, under moderate conditions.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Two techniques they use are Morse-Novikov theory and graph representation theory.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] For example, the tameness requirement can be replaced by the much weaker condition, continuous.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The proof of the structure theorem relies on the base domain being field, so not many attempts have been made on persistence homology with torsion.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Frosini defined a pseudometric on this specific module and proved its stability.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] One of its novelty is that it doesn't depend on some classification theory to define the metric.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] One advantage of category theory is its ability to lift concrete results to a higher level, showing relationships between seemingly unconnected objects.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Peter Bubenik et al. offers a short introduction of category theory fitted for TDA.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Category theory is the language of modern algebra, and has been widely used in the study of algebraic geometry and topology.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] It has been noted that "the key observation of is that the persistence diagram produced by depends only on the algebraic structure carried by this diagram." The use of category theory in TDA has proved to be fruitful.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] One advantage of using category theory in TDA is a clearer understanding of concepts and the discovery of new relationships between proofs.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The understanding of the correspondence between interleaving and matching is of huge importance, since matching has been the method used in the beginning (modified from Morse theory).
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] A summary of works can be found in Vin de Silva et al.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Many theorems can be proved much more easily in a more intuitive setting.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Another example is the relationship between the construction of different complexes from point clouds.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] It has long been noticed that Čech and Vietoris-Rips complexes are related.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The essential relationship between Cech and Rips complexes can be seen much more clearly in categorical language.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The language of category theory also helps cast results in terms recognizable to the broader mathematical community.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Bottleneck distance is widely used in TDA because of the results on stability with respect to the bottleneck distance.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] In fact, the interleaving distance is the terminal object in a poset category of stable metrics on multidimensional persistence modules in a prime field.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Sheaves, a central concept in modern algebraic geometry, are intrinsically related to category theory.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Roughly speaking, sheaves are the mathematical tool for understanding how local information determines global information.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Justin Curry regards level set persistence as the study of fibers of continuous functions.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The objects that he studies are very similar to those by MAPPER, but with sheaf theory as the theoretical foundation.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Although no breakthrough in the theory of TDA has yet used sheaf theory, it is promising since there are many beautiful theorems in algebraic geometry relating to sheaf theory.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] For example, a natural theoretical question is whether different filtration methods result in the same output.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Stability is of central importance to data analysis, since real data carry noises.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] By usage of category theory, Bubenik et al. have distinguished between soft and hard stability theorems, and proved that soft cases are formal.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The soft stability theorem asserts that $HF$ is Lipschitz continuous, and the hard stability theorem asserts that J is Lipschitz continuous.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Bottleneck distance is widely used in TDA.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The isometry theorem asserts that the **interleaving distance** $d_{I}$ is equal to the bottleneck distance.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Bubenik et al. have abstracted the definition to that between functors $F,G\colon P\to D$ when ${\textstyle P}$ is equipped with a sublinear projection or superlinear family, in which still remains a pseudometric.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] A $(\Gamma ,K)$ -interleaving between F and G consists of natural transformations $\varphi \colon F\Rightarrow G\Gamma$ and $\psi \colon G\Rightarrow FK$ , such that $(\psi \Gamma )=\varphi F\eta _{K\Gamma }$ and $(\varphi \Gamma )=\psi G\eta _{\Gamma K}$ .
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] These two results summarize many results on stability of different models of persistence.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] For the stability theorem of multidimensional persistence, please refer to the subsection of persistence.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The structure theorem is of central importance to TDA; as commented by G.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Carlsson, "what makes homology useful as a discriminator between topological spaces is the fact that there is a classification theorem for finitely generated abelian groups".
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] (see the fundamental theorem of finitely generated abelian groups).
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The main argument used in the proof of the original structure theorem is the standard structure theorem for finitely generated modules over a principal ideal domain.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] However, this argument fails if the indexing set is $(\mathbb {R} ,\leq )$ .
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] In general, not every persistence module can be decomposed into intervals.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Many attempts have been made at relaxing the restrictions of the original structure theorem.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The case for pointwise finite-dimensional persistence modules indexed by a locally finite subset of $\mathbb {R}$ is solved based on the work of Webb.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The most notable result is done by Crawley-Boevey, which solved the case of $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Crawley-Boevey's theorem states that any pointwise finite-dimensional persistence module is a direct sum of interval modules.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] To understand the definition of his theorem, some concepts need introducing.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] An **interval** in $(\mathbb {R} ,\leq )$ is defined as a subset $I\subset \mathbb {R}$ having the property that if $r,t\in I$ and if there is an $s\in \mathbb {R}$ such that $r\leq s\leq t$ , then $s\in I$ as well.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] An **interval module** $k_{I}$ assigns to each element $s\in I$ the vector space k and assigns the zero vector space to elements in $\mathbb {R} \setminus I$ .
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] All maps $\rho _{s}^{t}$ are the zero map, unless $s,t\in I$ and $s\leq t$ , in which case $\rho _{s}^{t}$ is the identity map.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Although the result of Crawley-Boevey is a very powerful theorem, it still doesn't extend to the q-tame case.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] A persistence module is **q-tame** if the rank of $\rho _{s}^{t}$ is finite for all $s<t$ .
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] There are examples of q-tame persistence modules that fail to be pointwise finite.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] However, it turns out that a similar structure theorem still holds if the features that exist only at one index value are removed.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] This holds because the infinite dimensional parts at each index value do not persist, due to the finite-rank condition.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Formally, the observable category $\mathrm {Ob}$ is defined as $\mathrm {Pers} /\mathrm {Eph}$ , in which $\mathrm {Eph}$ denotes the full subcategory of $\mathrm {Pers}$ whose objects are the ephemeral modules ( $\rho _{s}^{t}=0$ whenever $s<t$ ).
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Note that the extended results listed here do not apply to zigzag persistence, since the analogue of a zigzag persistence module over $\mathbb {R}$ is not immediately obvious.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Real data is always finite, and so its study requires us to take stochasticity into account.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Statistical analysis gives us the ability to separate true features of the data from artifacts introduced by random noise.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Persistent homology has no inherent mechanism to distinguish between low-probability features and high-probability features.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] One way to apply statistics to topological data analysis is to study the statistical properties of topological features of point clouds.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The study of random simplicial complexes offers some insight into statistical topology.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Katharine Turner et al. offers a summary of work in this vein.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] A second way is to study probability distributions on the persistence space.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] This space is fairly complicated; for example, it is not complete under the bottleneck metric.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The first attempt made to study it is by Yuriy Mileyko et al.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The space of persistence diagrams $D_{p}$ in their paper is defined as $D_{p}:=\left\{d\mid \sum _{x\in d}\left(2\inf _{y\in \Delta }\lVert x-y\rVert \right)^{p}<\infty \right\}$ where $\Delta$ is the diagonal line in $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ .
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] A nice property is that $D_{p}$ is complete and separable in the Wasserstein metric $W_{p}(u,v)=\left(\inf _{\gamma \in \Gamma (u,v)}\int _{\mathbb {X} \times \mathbb {X} }\rho ^{p}(x,y)\,\mathrm {d} \gamma (x,y)\right)^{1/p}$ .
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Expectation, variance, and conditional probability can be defined in the Fréchet sense.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] This allows many statistical tools to be ported to TDA.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Works on null hypothesis significance test, confidence intervals, and robust estimates are notable steps.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] A third way is to consider the cohomology of probabilistic space or statistical systems directly, called information structures and basically consisting in the triple ( $\Omega ,\Pi ,P$ ), sample space, random variables and probability laws.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Random variables are considered as partitions of the n atomic probabilities (seen as a probability (n-1)-simplex, $|\Omega |=n$ ) on the lattice of partitions ( $\Pi _{n}$ ).
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The random variables or modules of measurable functions provide the cochain complexes while the coboundary is considered as the general homological algebra first discovered by Gerhard Hochschild with a left action implementing the action of conditioning.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The first cocycle condition corresponds to the chain rule of entropy, allowing to derive uniquely up to the multiplicative constant, Shannon entropy as the first cohomology class.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The consideration of a deformed left-action generalises the framework to Tsallis entropies.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The information cohomology is an example of ringed topos.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Multivariate k-Mutual information appear in coboundaries expressions, and their vanishing, related to cocycle condition, gives equivalent conditions for statistical independence.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Minima of mutual-informations, also called synergy, give rise to interesting independence configurations analog to homotopical links.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Because of its combinatorial complexity, only the simplicial subcase of the cohomology and of information structure has been investigated on data.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Applied to data, those cohomological tools quantifies statistical dependences and independences, including Markov chains and conditional independence, in the multivariate case.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Notably, mutual-informations generalize correlation coefficient and covariance to non-linear statistical dependences.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Persistence landscapes, introduced by Peter Bubenik, are a different way to represent barcodes, more amenable to statistical analysis.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The space of persistence landscapes is very nice: it inherits all good properties of barcode representation (stability, easy representation, etc.), but statistical quantities can be readily defined, and some problems in Y.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Mileyko et al.'s work, such as the non-uniqueness of expectations, can be overcome.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Effective algorithms for computation with persistence landscapes are available.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Another approach is to use revised persistence, which is image, kernel and cokernel persistence.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] More than one way exists to classify the applications of TDA.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Perhaps the most natural way is by field.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Another way is by distinguishing the techniques by G.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Topological data analysis and persistent homology have had impacts on Morse theory.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Morse theory has played a very important role in the theory of TDA, including on computation.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Some work in persistent homology has extended results about Morse functions to tame functions or, even to continuous functions.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Deheuvels long before the invention of persistent homology extends Morse theory to all continuous functions.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] One recent result is that the category of Reeb graphs is equivalent to a particular class of cosheaf.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] This is motivated by theoretical work in TDA, since the Reeb graph is related to Morse theory and MAPPER is derived from it.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The proof of this theorem relies on the interleaving distance.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Persistent homology is closely related to spectral sequences.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] In particular the algorithm bringing a filtered complex to its canonical form permits much faster calculation of spectral sequences than the standard procedure of calculating $E_{p,q}^{r}$ groups page by page.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Zigzag persistence may turn out to be of theoretical importance to spectral sequences.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The Database of Original & Non-Theoretical Uses of Topology (DONUT) is a database of scholarly articles featuring practical applications of topological data analysis to various areas of science.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] DONUT was started in 2017 by Barbara Giunti, Janis Lazovskis, and Bastian Rieck, and as of October 2023 currently contains 447 articles.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] DONUT was featured in the November 2023 issue of the *Notices of the American Mathematical Society*.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] The stability property of topological features to small perturbations has been applied to make Graph Neural Networks robust against adversaries.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Arafat et. al. proposed a robustness framework which systematically integrates both local and global topological graph feature representations, the impact of which is controlled by the robust regularized topological loss.
[src:umap-embedding/topological-data-analysis] Given the attacker's budget, they derived stability guarantees on the node representations, establishing an important connection between Topological stability and Adversarial ML.
